#X text 200 275 500hz: 4th order (Q = 0.5);
#X text 211 338 500hz: 4th order (Q = 1);
#X text 419 70 Let's dive into the behaviour of different orders. To the left we can test how duplicating a biquad output of two 1st order allpass filters correspond to a 2nd order allpass with Q = 0.5! We also see how the phase shift doubles from 90 to 180º (a full phase opposition). While a 1st order filter can only go from 0º (at DC) to 180º (at Nyquist) \, a 2nd orfer has a full 360º cycle. Hence \, it's normal to stack 2nd order allpass filters in cascade \, cause each 2nd order section represents a full cycle., f 80;
#X text 419 177 A 4th order allpass with double the center frequency even further to 360º \, which makes it go back to 0! We also now see two points where the phase reaches 180º full opposition. A 4th order has two full cycles (720º in total). We need an odd number of 2nd order sections to have the center frequency sit at a full phase opposition. So a 6th order (3 sections) has three full cycles and the phase opposition points \, where the middle one is the center frequency., f 80;
#X text 517 270 Setting the Q in the 2nd order allpass filter changes the slope and where the full phase opposition points will be for two and more sections. For an odd number of sections \, we keep the center full opposition point at the center frequency and the Q only sets where the other ones are. For an even number of sections \, the Q interferes with all opposition points., f 66;
#X obj 414 421 bicoeff2 allpass, f 8;
#X msg 105 297 1.86237 -0.867104 0.867104 -1.86237 1 1.86237 -0.867104 0.867104 -1.86237 1, f 39;
